#!/usr/bin/env ssc
---
name: v2-multiline-list-literal
description: v2 fence extractor swallowed a multi-line [ list literal as a phantom multi-line import
backends: [int]
---

# v2 multi-line `[ … ]` list literal crashes the fence extractor

A bare `[` opening a MULTI-LINE list literal (elements on the following
lines) was misclassified by `FrontendBridge.filterImportLines` as the start
of a multi-line import directive (`[A,\n B](path.ssc)`). Finding no closing
`](….ssc)` line, it swallowed the entire rest of the fence — so the merged
source ended mid-expression and scala.meta then failed with
`illegal start of simple expression` on the NEXT `def`. Inline (`f([1, 2])`)
and single-line-in-parens (`f(\n [1, 2]\n)`) both parsed; only the multi-line
opener broke. v1 parses this fine on every backend.

Fix: `filterImportLines` only consumes a multi-line import when a real
`](….ssc)` close actually follows through ident-list continuations;
otherwise the line is code and is kept.

Found 2026-07-09 minimizing the `datatable-static-spa` corpus parse crash
(its `staticDataTable(rows, [ … ], [ … ])` nested multi-line list literals).

```scalascript
def pick(xs: List[Int], ys: List[Int]): Int =
  xs.length * 100 + ys.length

val n = pick(
  [
    1,
    2,
    3
  ],
  [
    9
  ]
)

def afterList(): Int = 42

println(n + afterList())
```
